2026-03-24 | Product Matrix Except Self (2D)

Question
Return the matrix where each cell contains product of all other elements.

	Approach
1.	Flatten matrix into 1D traversal order.
2.	Compute:
		prefix product array  
		suffix product array  

3.	For each index i:
		result[i] = prefix[i-1] * suffix[i+1]

4.	Map back to 2D matrix.

5.	Handle modulo at each step.

	Time Complexity
	O(n × m)

	Space Complexity
	O(n × m)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> constructProductMatrix(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {

        int n = grid.size();
        int m = grid[0].size();
        int MOD = 12345;

        int size = n * m;
        vector<int> arr(size);

        // flatten
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<m;j++){
                arr[i*m + j] = grid[i][j] % MOD;
            }
        }

        vector<int> prefix(size,1), suffix(size,1);

        for(int i=1;i<size;i++){
            prefix[i] = (prefix[i-1] * arr[i-1]) % MOD;
        }

        for(int i=size-2;i>=0;i--){
            suffix[i] = (suffix[i+1] * arr[i+1]) % MOD;
        }

        vector<vector<int>> ans(n, vector<int>(m));

        for(int i=0;i<size;i++){
            int val = (prefix[i] * suffix[i]) % MOD;
            ans[i/m][i%m] = val;
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

	Key Insight
Instead of recomputing product for every cell (O(n²m²)),
we reuse prefix and suffix products to achieve O(nm).

This is a 2D extension of:
	“Product of Array Except Self” without division.
